pred_text:
We can use polynomial long division to divide $x^9 + px^6 + qx^3 + r$ by $x^3 - 3x^2 + 4x - 1$ to find the quotient and remainder.  We have \begin{align*}
x^3 - 3x^2 + 4x - 1 \enclose{longdiv}{x^9 + px^6 + qx^3 + r}\\
\begin{array}{r}
x^6 - 3x^5 + 4x^4 - x^3 \\
\cline{2-5}
\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{r}
px^6 + (p-3)x^5 + (4p-3x^4 + (4q-3)x^3 + (4r-1)x^2 \\
\cline{2-5}
\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{r}
\end{array}\\
\end{align*}  For the remainder to be zero, we must have $4r-1=0,$ $4q-3=0,$ and $p-3=0.$  Solving these equations, we find $r=1/4,$ $q=3/4,$ and $p=3.$  Therefore, the answer is $(p,q,r) = \boxed{(3,3/4,1/4)}.$
#### (3,3/4,1/4)

We can use the power-reduction formula to express $(\sin x)^7$ in terms of sines and cosines.  We have
\begin{align*}
(\sin x)^7 &= \left(\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2i}\right)^7 \\
&= \frac{1}{2^7i^7} (e^{7ix} - 7e^{5ix} + 21e^{3ix} - 35e^{ix} + 35e^{-ix} - 21e^{-3ix} + 7e^{-5ix} - e^{-7ix}) \\
&= \frac{1}{128} (e^{7ix} - 7e^{5ix} + 21e^{3ix} - 35e^{ix} + 35e^{-ix} - 21e^{-3ix} + 7e^{-5ix} - e^{-7ix}).
\end{align*}We can then use the angle addition formula to express this as a sum of sines.  We have
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{128} (e^{7ix} - 7e^{5ix} + 21e^{3ix} - 35e^{ix} + 35e^{-ix} - 21e^{-3ix} + 7e^{-5ix} - e^{-7ix}) &= \frac{1}{128} (2\sin 7x + 2\sin 5x + 2\sin 3x + 2\sin x) \\
&= \frac{1}{64} (\sin 7x + \sin 5x + \sin 3x + \sin x).
\end{align*}Therefore, $d = \boxed{\frac{1}{64}}$.The answer is: \frac{1}{64}

